In professional "extra-heavy" formulations, the ratio of egg yolks to oil is increased compared to standard recipes. While a single yolk can technically emulsify several liters of oil, the resulting film around each droplet is thinner and more prone to rupture when the dressing is subjected to the acidity of buttermilk or the physical weight of blue cheese crumbles.4 Using two yolks per cup of oil provides a surplus of protein, ensuring a more resilient and thicker final product.19
The Influence of Temperature and pH
Successful emulsification is highly sensitive to the thermal state of the ingredients. It is a standard culinary and scientific recommendation that all components be used at room temperature.6 Room-temperature lipids are more fluid, allowing for the creation of smaller droplets, while room-temperature proteins are more flexible and able to unfold more effectively at the oil-water interface.6
Furthermore, the pH of the aqueous phase must be carefully controlled. The addition of vinegar or lemon juice lowers the pH to approximately 4.0, which is necessary for microbial stability and also influences the electrical charge of the yolk proteins.1 An overly acidic environment can cause the proteins to denature prematurely, leading to a thin or broken emulsion. Conversely, a lack of acid results in a "flat" flavor profile that cannot compete with the pungency of blue cheese.24
Lipid Analysis: Selecting the Optimal Oil for Blue Cheese Pairing
The choice of oil for a wedge salad mayonnaise is not merely a matter of health or smoke point; it is a critical flavor and structural decision. Because mayonnaise consists of up to 80% oil, the lipid profile will dominate the final dressing's character.24
The Bitterness Problem with Olive Oil
A common mistake in high-end homemade mayonnaise is the use of Extra Virgin Olive Oil (EVOO). While EVOO is prized for its complexity, its high concentration of polyphenols becomes problematic when subjected to high-shear mechanical blending.27 The rapid rotation of blender blades "bruises" the oil, causing it to oxidize and release intense bitter notes that can overwhelm the delicate creaminess of a blue cheese dressing.8
Avocado Oil vs. Seed Oils
For a steakhouse-style wedge salad, a neutral oil with a high monounsaturated fat content is the gold standard. Avocado oil is particularly well-suited for this application due to its mild, buttery flavor and superior oxidative stability.9

