Step-by-Step Production Protocol
1. Preparation and Thermal Equalization Ensure the egg yolks and avocado oil are at room temperature (approximately 70°F/21°C). This is the most important step for guaranteeing a stable emulsion.6
2. Layering the Reactants Use a tall, narrow jar or a 2-cup glass beaker that is only slightly wider than the head of the immersion blender. Add the yolks, vinegar, mustard, salt, sugar, water, and xanthan gum to the bottom of the jar. Pour the avocado oil directly on top. Allow the mixture to settle for 60 seconds so the xanthan gum can begin to hydrate in the aqueous layer at the bottom.15
3. Initial Phase Emulsification Lower the immersion blender into the jar until the head is firmly pressed against the bottom, completely covering the egg yolk mixture. Turn the blender on its highest speed setting. Do not move the blender. Hold it still for 20 to 30 seconds.19 You will see a thick, white emulsion begin to form at the base and slowly climb up the sides of the jar.19
4. Vertical Integration Once the bottom third of the jar is opaque and thick, begin to very slowly tilt and lift the blender head. As you lift, the oil from the top layer will be sucked down into the vortex and emulsified. Use a slow, rhythmic up-and-down motion until all the oil is incorporated and no streaks remain.19
5. Final Hydration and Cold Setting Process the mixture for an additional 15 seconds after it appears finished to ensure the xanthan gum is fully dispersed and the droplets are at their smallest diameter.15 Transfer the mayonnaise to a chilled glass container and refrigerate for at least one hour. This "cold set" allows the lipids to solidify slightly, resulting in a mayonnaise that can hold its shape on a spoon.25
Integrating the Mayo into the Master Wedge Dressing
The homemade mayonnaise produced by this protocol is a "concentrate" of structural stability. When combining it with the other components of the wedge salad dressing (buttermilk, sour cream, and blue cheese), the following technical tips will ensure the final result is never runny.
The "Hide the Mayo" Strategy
Professional chefs often use a "hide the mayo" technique to ensure that the final dressing tastes like fresh dairy and blue cheese rather than a jar of condiment. This is achieved by using a high-quality vinegar (like Champagne or Sherry vinegar) and fresh garlic marinated in that vinegar for 10 minutes before blending.25 This "blooming" of the garlic mutes its raw harshness and infuses the entire dressing with a sophisticated, integrated flavor.25
Handling the Buttermilk Dilution
Because this mayonnaise is stabilized with xanthan gum, it will "fight" the thinning effect of the buttermilk. However, the buttermilk should still be added gradually.
Whisk the Bases: Start by whisking the stabilized homemade mayonnaise and full-fat sour cream together until smooth. These two thick components form the structural "backbone" of the dressing.10
Gradual Thinning: Add the buttermilk one tablespoon at a time. After three or four tablespoons, the dressing should still be thick enough to leave a heavy coating on the back of a spoon (nappe consistency).11
The Blue Cheese Infusion: For the most flavorful "master" dressing, microwave half of your blue cheese crumbles for 10 seconds until they are soft and slightly melty. Whisk these directly into the base. This incorporates the actual cheese into the emulsion, thickening it further and ensuring every bite has a blue cheese essence.25 Fold in the remaining whole crumbles at the very end to provide the signature chunky texture.25
Seasoning for the Steakhouse Profile
To achieve the "steakhouse secret" flavor profile, two additions are often necessary: Worcestershire sauce and white pepper.
Worcestershire Sauce: Adds an "indescribable" umami layer that bridges the gap between the creamy dressing and the savory steak or bacon.25
White Pepper: Unlike black pepper, white pepper provides a sharp, clean heat that blends invisibly into the white dressing, maintaining the pristine aesthetic of the wedge salad.11
Troubleshooting and Corrective Measures
Even with a master recipe, variables such as egg size or ambient humidity can affect the final viscosity of an emulsion.
Fixing a Runny Dressing
If, after combining all ingredients, the blue cheese dressing still feels too thin for a wedge salad, do not add more buttermilk. Instead:
Add More Mayo: Whisk in an additional 2 tablespoons of your stabilized mayo. The xanthan gum content will quickly tighten the mixture.3
Strain the Sour Cream: If using a lower-quality sour cream with high whey content, strain it through a coffee filter for 2 hours before use to remove excess liquid.12
The "Smash" Method: Use a fork to smash more of the blue cheese crumbles against the side of the bowl. The released fats and proteins from the cheese act as natural thickeners.12
Fixing a Broken Mayo Batch
If the mayonnaise fails to emulsify and looks like a curdled soup of oil and eggs, all is not lost.
The Fresh Yolk Rescue: Place one fresh, room-temperature egg yolk and 1 teaspoon of water in a clean jar. Begin blending and very slowly (drop-by-drop) drizzle the failed, runny mixture into the new yolk. This restarts the emulsion and is the most reliable way to save the ingredients.17
Microbiological Considerations and Shelf Life
Homemade mayonnaise lacks the heavy-duty preservatives found in commercial jars. The stability of this recipe is derived from its high acid content and refrigeration.
Storage: The dressing should be stored in an airtight glass container in the coldest part of the refrigerator. It will remain fresh and structurally stable for 5 to 7 days.10
Food Safety: Because this recipe uses raw egg yolks, it is recommended to use "impeccably fresh" eggs from a trusted source or pasteurized eggs if serving to vulnerable populations.7
Flavor Maturation: The flavor of the dressing, particularly the blue cheese and garlic, will intensify significantly after 24 hours of refrigeration. For the best results, prepare the dressing one day before serving the wedge salad.25
Conclusion
The creation of a homemade mayonnaise specifically for the wedge salad is an exercise in applied food science. By focusing on high-viscosity stabilization—achieved through a dual-yolk protein matrix and the precise application of xanthan gum—the home cook can produce a replacement for store-bought mayo that is not only superior in flavor but also robust enough to support the heavy, chunky requirements of a steakhouse blue cheese dressing. Using avocado oil ensures a luxurious finish without bitterness, and the immersion blender technique guarantees a microscopic droplet size that defines the texture of a truly "master" recipe. When these elements are combined, the resulting dressing will cling flawlessly to every crevice of the iceberg wedge, providing a perfectly balanced, high-yield-stress coating that elevates the salad to a professional standard.



